{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c5e2e735-2ed5-4047-9c40-67edab853215","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n1. **User-level crashes:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level crashes:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for files named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**You can also use:**\n- **Console.app** → sidebar → *Crash Reports*\n- `log show --predicate 'eventMessage contains \"YourAppName\"' --last 1h`\n\n**For core dumps** (if you want a full memory dump instead):\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nThen re-run your app — the core file lands in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n**Tip:** The `.ips` crash log usually has enough info (faulting thread, backtrace, signal). If you need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames in that `.ips` file, I can help with that too.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7042b818-f4b8-4ed0-8760-d43c80b89ddf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.","outputTokens":336,"requestId":"A0C1:389D7E:96332D:B865DC:6A01366E"},"id":"237286df-7434-4c7e-82eb-bd71fd71a8cf","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:52:56.418Z","parentId":"53f81ca2-0f8f-4f4d-bc92-57f3d11459af"}
